ce:section.ce:para:
The Si-CDs used for LSCs were prepared by one-step solvothermal approach using CA as carbon source, DCD as nitrogen source and APTES as silicone precursors in a mixture of H2O and EtOH, in which the formation of CDs is accompanied by the hydrolysis–condensation of APTES (Fig. 2
                     ). As a result, the CDs are anchored in the Si-O-Si network structures, which can effectively inhibit the aggregation quenching of CDs. In addition, such three-dimensional network structure of the silicone is able to endow the Si-CDs composite good stability, which is in favor of their application in LSCs. As is shown in Fig. 3
                     a, the Si-CDs are quasi-spherical particles with the size of about 2 μm. The CDs in the Si-CDs can be clearly observed in the HRTEM image (Fig. 3b). It can be seen that the CDs are spherical shaped and display a narrow size distribution with an average diameter of around 3.8 ± 0.2 nm. And the CDs have highly crystalline carbon structure with an interplanar distances of about 0.24 nm by the 2D lattice fringes of the CDs, which is attributed to the (100) lattice plane of graphitic carbon [19,41]. The FTIR spectrum of Si-CDs showed in Fig. S1 further demonstrates that the CDs are anchored in silicone network supported by Si-O-Si (strong stretching vibration at 1133 cm−1, respectively, which verifies the formation of a cross-linked silicone network owing to the hydrolysis and condensation of APTES) [42]. The absorption peaks at 3400 and 1650 cm−1 are assigned to the N–H and CO-NH stretching vibration, respectively, indicating that the CDs and silicone network are linked through covalent bonds [43–44]. Fig. 3d presents that Si-CDs have a distinct absorption at 215 nm, which is attributed to the π-π* transitions of C = C bonds and the absorption peaks at ca. 304 nm, 345 nm and 450 nm in the UV − vis spectra [45], which can be assigned to the n–π* transition of C = O [46]. In the PL spectra (Fig. 3d and Fig. S2), Si-CDs exhibit strong yellow-green emission when excited from 310 to 510 nm and the emission peaks show a slight red shift from 524 nm to 557 nm. The maximum fluorescence emission appears at 525 nm under 450 nm excitation. The fluorescence behavior is dependent on excitation, which is supposed to be attributed to the distribution of different emissive sites [47]. Compared to the CDs prepared by CA and DCD, the Si-CDs emit stronger fluorescence with the PLQY of 11.0%, which is much higher than that of CDs powder (only 2%, Fig. S3). This result suggests that the Si-CDs can effectively conquer the aggregation quenching effect of CDs. The average fluorescence lifetime of Si-CDs is 7.2 ns.
